{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n`canonical_tracker` (`src/rebar/_store/lock.py:81-84`, `os.path.realpath`) is the lock-path\nanchor that guarantees a symlinked-path caller and a real-path caller contend on the **same**\n`.ticket-write.lock` / `.ticket-write.lock.d` (`acquire` canonicalizes at `lock.py:289`).\nVALIDATED: zero test references `canonical_tracker`; the invariant is untested.\n\n## What\nAdd a test proving that two independent acquirers — one addressing the tracker by its real\npath, the other by a symlink to it — mutually exclude, in BOTH directions.\n\nDeterminism (no sleep race): the two acquirers are two independent `acquire()` calls, each\nopening its OWN file descriptor (fcntl leg) and attempting its OWN `os.mkdir` (mkdir leg).\nPer the Linux `flock(2)` contract, separate `open()` descriptions to the same file contend\neven within one process, and `os.mkdir` fails `EEXIST` on an existing dir regardless of\nprocess — so holding the lock via one path makes the second acquirer via the OTHER path\ndeterministically fail. The second acquirer uses `timeout=1, attempts=1` (a bounded 1s\nbudget); because the lock is genuinely held, it is GUARANTEED to exhaust that budget and\nraise `LockTimeout` — a deterministic outcome, not a timing race that a slow runner could\nflip. Teeth: were `canonical_tracker` not resolving the symlink, the two paths would key\ndifferent lock files, the second acquire would SUCCEED, and the `LockTimeout` assertion would\nfail — so the test genuinely exercises the canonicalization invariant.\n\n## Scope\n- `tests/unit/test_lock_stale_reclaim.py` — add the symlink/realpath lock-identity tests.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Holding the lock acquired via the REAL path, a second `acquire()` via a symlink to the\n      tracker raises `LockTimeout` (blocked); after release, the symlink caller acquires.\n- [ ] The reverse direction (hold via the symlink, contend via the real path) also raises\n      `LockTimeout`, then succeeds after release.\n- [ ] Both tests are deterministic (bounded `timeout=1, attempts=1`; the block is guaranteed\n      by a genuinely-held lock, not by sleep timing).\n- [ ] `make test` green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783796483375747001,"uuid":"58079ff2-d069-43cc-9fb2-c3fe3147b8bd"}